00:13:33,947 --> 00:13:37,615
  the conveyer belt feeding the 
  carder is marked in sections. 

229
00:13:37,617 --> 00:13:40,685
      they place one bundle     
        in each section.        

230
00:13:40,687 --> 00:13:42,354
     this steady, even input    

231
00:13:42,356 --> 00:13:46,825
    ensures that the machine    
  produces a consistent output. 

232
00:13:46,827 --> 00:13:48,693
       inside the carder,       

233
00:13:48,695 --> 00:13:51,062
    a series of combs spreads   
     the fibers over a drum,    

234
00:13:51,064 --> 00:13:54,966
     aligning them parallel     
         to each other.         

235
00:13:54,968 --> 00:14:00,572
this produces a thin, flat layer
    of fine fiber called web.   

236
00:14:00,574 --> 00:14:02,641
       web can be stacked       
       in several layers        

237
00:14:02,643 --> 00:14:03,842
        to make batting,        

238
00:14:03,844 --> 00:14:07,712
      the stuffing material     
      in quilts and duvets.     

239
00:14:07,714 --> 00:14:11,516
         batting can be         
  further processed into felt.  

240
00:14:11,518 --> 00:14:14,786
    web can also be processed   
          into roving,          

241
00:14:14,788 --> 00:14:17,055
  a long thick stream of fiber  

242
00:14:17,057 --> 00:14:19,991
  which crafts people hand spin 
           into yarn,           

243
00:14:19,993 --> 00:14:22,661
  or which high-speed machines  
        here at the mill        

244
00:14:22,663 --> 00:14:25,730
  spin into store-bought yarn.  

245
00:14:25,732 --> 00:14:29,334
  the roving deck on the carder 
compresses the web into a stream

246
00:14:29,336 --> 00:14:32,103
        while rotating it       
   to hold the aligned fibers   

247
00:14:32,105 --> 00:14:34,872
     in a snake like shape.     

248
00:14:34,874 --> 00:14:37,075
      to make what's known      
         as woolen yarn,        

249
00:14:37,077 --> 00:14:40,145
           the roving           
  goes directly to the spinner. 

250
00:14:40,147 --> 00:14:43,014
 however, to make what's called 
       semi-worsted yarn,       

251
00:14:43,016 --> 00:14:45,149
          this machine,         
      called a draw frame,      

252
00:14:45,151 --> 00:14:47,419
       must first combine       
       two or more rovings      

253
00:14:47,421 --> 00:14:52,023
    into a consistent stream    
        called a sliver.        

254
00:14:52,025 --> 00:14:53,424
      the thinner the yarn,     

255
00:14:53,426 --> 00:14:57,495
   the more often the rovings   
  pass through the draw frame.  

256
00:14:57,497 --> 00:14:59,297
    finally, several slivers    

257
00:14:59,299 --> 00:15:01,566
         simultaneously         
       enter the spinner,       

258
00:15:01,568 --> 00:15:03,968
which twists each one separately
      through a combination     

259
00:15:03,970 --> 00:15:06,438
     of pressure and speed.     

260
00:15:06,440 --> 00:15:08,507
        the next machine,       
        called the plyer,       

261
00:15:08,509 --> 00:15:11,576
       then forms the yarn      
  by twisting multiple singles  

262
00:15:11,578 --> 00:15:14,179
            together            
   in the opposite direction.   

263
00:15:14,181 --> 00:15:15,180
      twisting two singles,     

264
00:15:15,182 --> 00:15:18,249
          for example,          
      makes a two-ply yarn.     

265
00:15:18,251 --> 00:15:20,051
   the mill produces different  
         weights of yarn        

266
00:15:20,053 --> 00:15:22,119
       from lace to bulky,      

267
00:15:22,121 --> 00:15:24,655
      by varying the volume     
        of fiber per ply,       

268
00:15:24,657 --> 00:15:27,926
 as well as the spinning speed. 

269
00:15:27,928 --> 00:15:29,794
      they mount the spools     
        of finished yarn        

270
00:15:29,796 --> 00:15:32,063
      on the skein winder.      

271
00:15:32,065 --> 00:15:35,934
   a skein is a bundle of yarn  
that's first wound then twisted.

272
00:15:35,936 --> 00:15:39,738
  they set the machine to wind  
   a specific length of yarn.   

273
00:15:39,740 --> 00:15:41,072
         when it stops,         

274
00:15:41,074 --> 00:15:44,209
 they tie the skein on two ends 
         and remove it.         

275
00:15:44,211 --> 00:15:48,346
     then they dye the yarn     
 or leave it its natural color. 

276
00:15:48,348 --> 00:15:51,416
   some mills dye their fleece  
         after washing,         

277
00:15:51,418 --> 00:15:53,685
     prior to processing it     
           into yarn.           

278
00:15:53,687 --> 00:15:56,888
         the final step         
   is to hand-twist the skein.  

279
00:15:56,890 --> 00:16:01,159
 they also wind yarn into balls 
           and cones.           

280
00:16:01,161 --> 00:16:05,029
    warm and water repellent,   
 this silky, smooth alpaca yarn 

281
00:16:05,031 --> 00:16:10,402
      is all set to be knit     
  or woven into a cozy woolen.  

282
00:16:26,720 --> 00:16:28,720
   narrator: the utility knife  
 is known by many other names --

283
00:16:28,722 --> 00:16:31,789
    carpet knife, box cutter,   
        sheet-rock knife,       

284
00:16:31,791 --> 00:16:34,793
 and craft knife are just a few.

285
00:16:34,795 --> 00:16:36,862
         all those names        
      reflect the many uses     

286
00:16:36,864 --> 00:16:40,866
   for this retractable knife   
 and its incredible versatility.

287
00:16:40,868 --> 00:16:43,869
  it comes in handy every time. 

288
00:16:46,205 --> 00:16:50,074
   in 70 years, the design of   
 this retractable utility knife 

289
00:16:50,076 --> 00:16:52,010
   hasn't really changed much.  

290
00:16:52,012 --> 00:16:55,080
     why mess with a concept    
           that works?          

291
00:16:55,082 --> 00:16:57,482
          a hollow case         
    with an interlocking nose   

292
00:16:57,484 --> 00:17:00,819
         for the blade,         
held together by a single screw.

293
00:17:00,821 --> 00:17:05,556
   it can be easily unscrewed   
 to access spare blades inside. 

294
00:17:05,558 --> 00:17:10,562
to make the blades, carbon steel
    uncoils into a die press.   

295
00:17:10,564 --> 00:17:14,032
   a roller takes up the slack  
       as the steel inches      

296
00:17:14,034 --> 00:17:15,267
    forward for each forming.   

297
00:17:17,371 --> 00:17:19,170
   the press scores the steel   

298
00:17:19,172 --> 00:17:21,239
     to rough out the shape     
         of the blades,         

299
00:17:21,241 --> 00:17:24,042
  punches notches for attaching 
       them to the handle,      

300
00:17:24,044 --> 00:17:27,145
 and stamps product information 
           onto them.           

301
00:17:30,851 --> 00:17:34,519
at this point, the steel is just
a little stiffer than tin foil. 

302
00:17:34,521 --> 00:17:38,522
  a trip through a 25-foot-long 
     furnace toughens it up.    

303
00:17:38,524 --> 00:17:42,060
    exposed to scorching heat   
   and then quenched by water,  

304
00:17:42,062 --> 00:17:46,131
the steel hardens significantly.

305
00:17:46,133 --> 00:17:49,066
      after the brand name      
 has been printed on the steel, 

306
00:17:49,068 --> 00:17:51,803
   the ribbon of blades rides   
   through a grinding station   

307
00:17:51,805 --> 00:17:55,606
         with different         
     stone-grinding wheels.     

308
00:17:55,608 --> 00:17:58,743
  they sharpen the steel edge.  

309
00:17:58,745 --> 00:18:01,212
      the steel now passes      
     under an induction coil    

310
00:18:01,214 --> 00:18:04,649
  that radiates heat to further 
    harden the cutting edge.    

311
00:18:06,553 --> 00:18:08,285
  a machine called the breaker  

312
00:18:08,287 --> 00:18:11,222
         snaps the steel        
     along the score lines.     

313
00:18:11,224 --> 00:18:13,358
          it spits out          
  the unwanted triangular bits  

314
00:18:13,360 --> 00:18:15,293
       between the blades       
         for recycling.         

315
00:18:15,295 --> 00:18:18,096
           the blades           
     flow out of the breaker    

316
00:18:18,098 --> 00:18:20,031
    and into a steel channel.   

317
00:18:20,033 --> 00:18:24,169
       a pusher moves them      
  down the channel into a tray. 

318
00:18:24,171 --> 00:18:29,307
   this system snaps and packs  
      250 blades a minute.      

319
00:18:29,309 --> 00:18:33,578
they insert one blade from every
production run into this tester.

320
00:18:33,580 --> 00:18:36,448
   the tester moves the blade   
   back and forth repeatedly    

321
00:18:36,450 --> 00:18:39,784
  to slice through thick stacks 
        of paper strips.        

322
00:18:39,786 --> 00:18:40,852
    this gives them a measure   

323
00:18:40,854 --> 00:18:44,255
    of the blade's sharpness    
         and durability.        

324
00:18:44,257 --> 00:18:47,325
     the transformation from    
blunt metal to razor sharp blade

325
00:18:47,327 --> 00:18:50,528
          is complete,          
  and the utility knife blades  

326
00:18:50,530 --> 00:18:52,530
            are ready           
    for the gripping part --    

327
00:18:52,532 --> 00:18:54,799
         the zinc case.         

328
00:18:54,801 --> 00:18:58,803
  they cast the back and front  
      of the case in a die.     

329
00:18:58,805 --> 00:19:02,740
  the parts then bounce around  
       in a vibratory bowl      

330
00:19:02,742 --> 00:19:05,276
           along with           
  pyramid-shaped ceramic rocks. 

331
00:19:05,278 --> 00:19:09,280
          the friction          
    smoothes the rough edges.   

332
00:19:09,282 --> 00:19:11,749
     after about a half hour    
     in the vibratory bowl,     

333
00:19:11,751 --> 00:19:15,152
        the casing parts        
        are blemish free.       

334
00:19:15,154 --> 00:19:17,555
they head into the next station.

335
00:19:17,557 --> 00:19:20,892
   here, workers collect them   
  and examine them for defects  

336
00:19:20,894 --> 00:19:24,295
        as they hang them       
        on moving racks.        

337
00:19:24,297 --> 00:19:27,232
       the racks will take      
     the utility knife parts    

338
00:19:27,234 --> 00:19:29,567
     through a wash station     

339
00:19:29,569 --> 00:19:32,971
     to get rid of a dusting    
  of zinc and ceramic residue.  

340
00:19:34,774 --> 00:19:38,109
    it's kind of a power wash   
    for the knife case parts.   

341
00:19:38,111 --> 00:19:41,846
  they ride by a high-pressure  
sprayer for a thorough cleaning.

342
00:19:45,051 --> 00:19:48,119
           after that,          
they take a trip through a dryer

343
00:19:48,121 --> 00:19:50,788
         to prepare them        
    for a powder coat finish.   

344
00:19:50,790 --> 00:19:52,724
      once the powder coat      
          is baked on,          

345
00:19:52,726 --> 00:19:56,161
    it will protect the zinc    
  utility knife from corrosion. 

346
00:19:59,866 --> 00:20:02,000
         the powder coat        
    gives the utility knives    

347
00:20:02,002 --> 00:20:04,269
    a finish that's tougher     
    than conventional paint.    

348
00:20:10,343 --> 00:20:12,610
             heading            
  into the unload station now,  

349
00:20:12,612 --> 00:20:14,979
     a blast from an air gun    
 knocks the parts off the rack. 

350
00:20:21,555 --> 00:20:27,392
  thanks to the tough finish,   
  they land without a scratch.  

351
00:20:32,431 --> 00:20:35,099
     the utility-knife parts    
     are ready for assembly,    

352
00:20:35,101 --> 00:20:38,302
         and the worker         
uses a special fixture for that.

353
00:20:38,304 --> 00:20:41,839
   she places the bottom half   
          of the knife          

354
00:20:41,841 --> 00:20:44,843
   in a recess in the fixture.  

355
00:20:44,845 --> 00:20:46,845
     handling the blunt side    
         of the blades,         

356
00:20:46,847 --> 00:20:50,315
 she inserts three of them into 
 the case's storage compartment.

357
00:20:51,985 --> 00:20:55,787
     she also tucks the tab     
 of an information card into it.

358
00:20:55,789 --> 00:20:58,523
       next, she installs       
    the retractable mechanism   

359
00:20:58,525 --> 00:21:01,459
  for the utility knife blades. 

360
00:21:01,461 --> 00:21:04,262
    she places the other half   
   of the case on the assembly  

361
00:21:04,264 --> 00:21:07,932
 and then actuates an auto-screw
     gun to close the knife.    

362
00:21:09,469 --> 00:21:13,471
       they assemble over       
  40,000 utility knives per day 

363
00:21:13,473 --> 00:21:16,474
        at this factory.        

364
00:21:16,476 --> 00:21:19,077
    now, that's cutting edge.   

